        reason: 'On the advice of the astronomer Sosigenes of Alexandria, Caesar abandons the drifting lunar Roman calendar for a solar year of 365.25 days, inserting an intercalary day every four years. To realign the seasons, 46 BCE is extended to 445 days (the "year of confusion"); the reformed calendar begins January 1, 45 BCE. Plutarch records the reform within a generation.',
